{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ae91b444-5a48-4265-a31a-0df1cf90fffe","content":"The repo is empty locally, so I'll create the GitHub Actions workflow and walk you through the nuget.org configuration. Let me set everything up.","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"tooluse_JyrFMi07vt4ZuJuikgyeQ0","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Creating publish workflow"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"tooluse_GASAKG0ABtdmlWKffC4ll1","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"mkdir -p /tmp/sv-f6ebfe64f7d14d6f8d1bced929f9dc08/.github/workflows","description":"Create workflow directory"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Create workflow directory"}],"interactionId":"901df1d0-c98c-4a69-afab-87ea77fe5928","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The directory is empty. The user wants me to help set up trusted publishing for their .NET library. Let me:\n\n1. Check if there's a `.github/workflows` directory\n2. Explain the setup\n\nSince the repo is empty locally, I'll need to create the necessary files. The key components for NuGet trusted publishing via OIDC are:\n\n1. **NuGet.org setup**: Register a trusted publisher on nuget.org linking the GitHub repo/workflow\n2. **GitHub Actions workflow**: A workflow that uses OIDC to authenticate with nuget.org\n\nLet me create:\n1. The GitHub Actions workflow for publishing\n\n\n2. Explain the nuget.org configuration steps\n\nFor the workflow, I need to set `permissions: id-token: write` so it can request an OIDC token from GitHub, then use `dotnet nuget push` with that token as the API key to authenticate with nuget.org. On the nuget.org side, you configure a trusted publisher that specifies which GitHub repository and workflow can publish packages.\n\nWriting the workflow file... I need to clarify how NuGet actually handles the OIDC token in the workflow—whether it's automatically picked up or needs to be explicitly passed via the `--api-key` flag. The trusted publisher setup on nuget.org registers the repository details, but I'm working through exactly how the CLI receives and uses that token during the push operation. OIDC environment automatically. The exact mechanism depends on the NuGet CLI version, so I should verify the current best practice for 2024-2025. NuGet.org does support trusted publishing, which requires linking a trusted publisher on the package side and using `id-token: write` in GitHub Actions, but I'm uncertain whether `dotnet nuget push` needs an explicit token from the OIDC endpoint or handles it transparently. Let me work through both the GitHub and nuget.org setup to create a reliable workflow.\n\nBuilding the modern approach...","outputTokens":1743,"requestId":"2443:23E21D:1627614:18B88D2:6A051EAB"},"id":"592fbccb-4f7b-485e-87bc-b5722db47bd2","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:00:58.203Z","parentId":"0f5d82e3-3d15-4aa4-842c-a32745c49f18"}
