{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"92272c19-2fbd-4759-a54c-7a5e7cde133e","content":"The workflow is created at `.github/workflows/publish.yml`. Here's what you still need to do:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Create the GitHub Environment\n\nGo to **repo Settings → Environments → New environment** and create one named **`nuget-publish`**. This is referenced in the workflow and in the nuget.org trusted publisher config. You can optionally add protection rules (e.g., restrict to `v*` tags).\n\n### 2. Register the Trusted Publisher on nuget.org\n\nOn **nuget.org → Manage Packages → your package → Trusted Publishers** (or during initial package upload):\n\n| Field | Value |\n|---|---|\n| Repository owner | `myorg` |\n| Repository name | `mylib` |\n| Workflow filename | `publish.yml` |\n| Environment | `nuget-publish` |\n\nIf the package doesn't exist yet, you can register the trusted publisher *before* the first push at **nuget.org → Upload → Trusted Publishers → Add**.\n\n### 3. Publish\n\nTag a commit and push:\n\n```bash\ngit tag v1.0.0\ngit push origin v1.0.0\n```\n\nThe workflow will build, pack, and push to nuget.org using OIDC — **no API key or secret needed**.\n\n> **Note:** The OIDC auto-negotiation requires **.NET SDK 9+** (NuGet 6.13+). The workflow pins `dotnet-version: 9.0.x` for this reason. Make sure your `.csproj` targets a compatible TFM (e.g., `net8.0` or `net9.0`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"901df1d0-c98c-4a69-afab-87ea77fe5928","outputTokens":384,"requestId":"243C:36C28E:15D791A:186A801:6A051ED2"},"id":"55ce168b-2577-4b0a-b8de-f2fc61668970","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:01:16.515Z","parentId":"ef95ab93-9536-41e8-9b98-3e56923f4c62"}
